    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''The Middle Ages,'' by Niobe Way and Diane Hughes (Op-Ed, March 25), underscores compelling reasons that teachers need training about how to talk about race relations with middle schoolers.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''The Middle Ages,'' by Niobe Way and Diane Hughes (Op-Ed, March 25), underscores compelling reasons that teachers need training about how to talk about race relations with middle schoolers.</p>
        <p>Nine years ago, I began showing 1967's ''Guess Who's Coming to Dinner'' to my sixth-grade students. Viewing this film with a facilitator allows kids to examine their own -- and their family's -- feelings about race.</p>
        <p>Middle school students thrive after participating in discussions about just how and why race matters. To succeed in school, adolescents need safe classrooms that help them untangle the barrage of mixed messages that they're just beginning to notice swirling around them about their own race, place and social class.</p>
        <p>Michael Kandel  Douglaston, Queens</p>
      </block>
